H0.text: Lower limb is the part of the body in which clubfoot, also known as talipes, is the most common congenital disorder of unknown cause present at birth.

H1.text: Upper limb is the body part in which clubfoot, also known as talipes, is the most common deformity, a congenital disorder of unknown cause.

H2.text: Genitals are the part of the body for which clubfoot, also known as talipes, is the most common congenital disorder of unknown cause.

H3.text: Cranium is the most common deformity of clubfoot, also known as talipes, which is a congenital disorder present at birth of unknown cause.

A4.text: Congenital clubfoot is the most common congenital malformation of the foot with an incidence of 1 per 1000 births.

A5.text: Clubfoot is a congenital or acquired defect where one or both feet are rotated inward and downward.
